FIFA DreamTeam

Tlotliso Jonas & Matthew Roberts

04/07/2020

Project Description

The aim of this project is to use data driven approach to examine the relationship between players statistics to guide building a winning soccer teams using the 2019 FIFA dataset. Three teams will be created, the first one is a team with a limited budget of 500 millions, the second one with the budget limit of 700 millions and the third team doesn’t have any budget limitations. These three teams will them be compared on their overall ratings and total value of the team. We first clean the data set, then examine relationship and distributions between variables. Thereafter the the regression models will build to select players per position and finally the linear programming optimization will be used to build the three teams.

It can be noted that the Value and Wage column have a strange format and will not be useful in numeric operations later if they have that format. In the code below we write a function and use it to clean up these two columns.

#A function for cleaning wage and value columns
fix_value<-function(value){
  clean_value<-str_remove(value,"â‚¬")
  if (str_detect(clean_value,"M"))
  {
     clean_value<-as.numeric(str_remove(clean_value,"M"))*1e6    
  }
  else if (str_detect(clean_value,"K"))
  {
     clean_value<-as.numeric(str_remove(clean_value,"K"))*1e3 
  }
  return (clean_value)
}

#Clean the wage and value columns
data$Value<-as.numeric(lapply(data$Value,fix_value)) 
data$Wage<-as.numeric(lapply(data$Wage,fix_value))

Data Understanding

We analyze different aspects of the data by plotting distributions of variables:

Preferred Foot

From the plot above it can be seen that most fifa players are right footed and there are also very few players who do not have foot preference.

Age Distribution

From the age distribution above it can be observed that most fifa players are between 20 to 25 years of age and it can also be noted that the youngest player is 16 years old while the oldest is 45 years old.

Positions Distributions

In this plot we observe the number of players per position and it can be noted that some positions such as goalkeeping and striker have a lot of players while other positions such as left forward and right forward are being played by very few players.

Wage Distribution

From the wage distribution above we can see that almost all the players earn about just less than 250 000 euros and very few players earn above 500 000 euros.

Value Distribution

Here we observe that there are some players that do not have any value associated with no value and this might be the free agent players and we also observe that most players are valued in millions with most players being valued less that 20 million euros.

Number of Skill Moves of Players Distribution

Here we observe that most players have 2 and 3 skill moves while very few players have 5 skill moves

Speciality Score Distribution

The speciality score displays the right skewness normal distribution behavior. Here we observe that most players have the speciality score of about 1600 to 1800.

Player Overall Rating Distribution

Model Development And Player Selection

In this section we develop criteria to select players that are going to be used later in developing the teams. The selected matrice in the previous section will be used to create a regression model to select overvalued and undervalued players per each position. The regression model will predict the value of players and those predicted values will be defined as fair values of players and when those fair values are compared to the actual value of players then players can be catergorised as undervalued and overvalued players. These undervalued players will be use later to construct two constrained teams.

Model Development

In this section we develop two functions, one for selecting top 10 undervalued players for a given the position and another one for selecting top 10 overvalued players for a given a position.

#A function to select undervalued players
undervalued<-function(position){
  cols<-c('ID','Name','Overall','Potential','Value','Position')
  pos<-filter(data[cols],Position==position)
  z<-(pos$Potential+pos$Overall)^15
  if (cor(z,pos$Value)<0.94) 
  {
    return ('Correlation is below 0.94')
  }else
  {
    pos$x<-z
    fit<-pos%>%
      lm(pos$Value ~ pos$x,data=.)
    
    coefs<-fit$coefficients
    
    players<-pos%>%mutate(fair_value=coefs[1]+coefs[2]*x)%>%
      filter(Value<fair_value)%>%
      top_n(10,Value)%>%
      select(-x)
    return (players)
  }
  
}
#A function to select overvalued players
overvalued<-function(position){
  cols<-c('ID','Name','Overall','Potential','Value','Position')
  pos<-filter(data[cols],Position==position)
  z<-(pos$Potential+pos$Overall)^15
  if (cor(z,pos$Value)<0.94) 
  {
    return ('Correlation is below 0.94')
  }else
  {
    pos$x<-z
    fit<-pos%>%
      lm(pos$Value ~ pos$x,data=.)
    
    coefs<-fit$coefficients
    
    players<-pos%>%mutate(fair_value=coefs[1]+coefs[2]*x)%>%
      filter(Value>fair_value)%>%
      top_n(10,Value)%>%
      select(-x)
    return (players)
  }
  
}

Teams Construction

In this section we use all use all the undervalued players above and use optimization technique to construct the first two constrained teams. Each team will have 20 players to play an attacking tactic and this formation is split by positions as follows:

  1. Goalkeeper(GK) - 2

  2. Defense (LB, RB, 3 X CB, RWB, LWB) - 7

  3. Midfield (CAM, CM, LDM, RDM, LCM, RCM) - 6

  4. Forward (ST, CF, LW, RW) - 5

Team 1

The code below uses r linear programming to select 20 players by maximizing the team overall and such that total value of the players is less or equal 500 million euros.

#combine all undervalued players into a single datafram
undervalue_players<-arrange(unique(rbind(ust,ucf,ulw,urw,ucam,ucm,uldm,urdm,ulcm,urcm,ulb,urb,ucb,urwb,ulwb,ugk,ulcb,urcb,ucdm,ulf)),desc(-ID))

molten_data<-melt(undervalue_players,id.vars = c('ID','Name'),value.name = 'Position',measure.vars = 'Position')
#create a constrain matrix (i.e. position constraints)
constraint_matrix<-acast(molten_data,Position ~ ID,fun.aggregate = length,value.var = 'Name' )

#get the number of positions
npos<-nrow(constraint_matrix)
#add value row to the constraint matrix (for the value constrain)
constraint_matrix<-rbind(constraint_matrix,Value=undervalue_players$Value)
#set the constraints direction per row
constraint_dir<-c(rep("==",npos),"<=")
#set the limit bounds 
constraint_limit<-c(rep(1,npos),500e6)
#solve using linear programming
lp_solution<-lp(direction = 'max',undervalue_players$Overall,constraint_matrix,constraint_dir,constraint_limit,all.int = T,transpose.constraints = T)

#The selected team
team1<-undervalue_players%>%
  filter(lp_solution$solution==1)%>%
  arrange(desc(Overall))

For the third team we dont just use undervalued players but we use all the players in the data set to select the 20 best players without any budget constraints and we do this using linear programming as well.

#required positions for the team
sel_positions<-c('GK','RCB','LB','RB','CB','LCB','CDM','LWB','RWB','CAM','CM','LDM','RDM','LCM','RCM','ST','CF','LW','RW','RF','RW')
players<-arrange(filter(data,data$Position %in% sel_positions),desc(-ID))

constraint_limit3<-rep(1,npos)
